<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="GREEN"><I>Rig Veda</I>, tr. by Ralph T.H. Griffith, [1896], at sacred-texts.com</FONT></P><HR></p>  <h3 align="center" align="center">HYMN XLI. A&#347;vins.</h3>  
<p>1. THAT general Car of yours, invoked by many a man, that comes to our libations, three-wheeled, meet for lauds,<br> That circumambient Car, worthy of sacrifice, we call with our pure hymns at earliest flush of dawn.<br> 2 Ye, O N&#257;satyas, mount that early-harnessed Car, that travels early, laden with its freight of balm,<br> Wherewith ye, Heroes, visit clans who sacrifice, even the poor man's worship where the priest attends.<br> 3 If to the deft Adhvaryu with the meath in hand, or to the Kindler firm in strength, the household friend,<br> Or to the sage's poured libations ye approach, come thence, O A&#347;vins, now to drink the offered meath.</p>  
